window.MODULES=window.MODULES||{};window.MODULES["pci"]={"slug": "pci", "title": "Percutaneous Coronary Intervention", "tagline": "The cath lab toolkit and the reasoning behind it: access, guides, wires, balloons and stents, intracoronary imaging and physiology, calcium modification, periprocedural antithrombotics, and the complications a fellow must manage at the table.", "level": 3, "readMin": 44, "takeaways": ["Radial-first access lowers bleeding and vascular complications and, in ACS, reduces mortality (guideline COR I, LOE A); confirm a dual palmar arch with the Barbeau test, not the older Allen test, before committing to the radial artery.", "Physiology decides the intermediate lesion: defer when FFR is above 0.80 or a resting index (iFR/RFR) is above 0.89, and never trust FFR in the acute infarct-related artery because microvascular stunning blunts hyperemia.", "Intracoronary imaging changes stent results: use IVUS or OCT to size the vessel, choose landing zones in normal reference segments, and confirm expansion with a minimal stent area target above roughly 5.5 mm2 (non-left-main) with full apposition and no edge dissection.", "Calcified lesions need modification before the stent, not after: recognize the undilatable lesion early and reach for non-compliant high-pressure balloons, scoring or cutting balloons, rotational or orbital atherectomy, or intravascular lithotripsy rather than stenting an under-expanded segment.", "Own the four table emergencies cold: coronary perforation graded by Ellis class (prolonged balloon, reversal, covered stent, pericardiocentesis), no-reflow (intracoronary adenosine, verapamil, nicardipine, nitroprusside), abrupt closure from dissection (stent the entry), and acute stent thrombosis.", "Antithrombotic strategy is individualized: aspirin plus a potent P2Y12 inhibitor (prasugrel or ticagrelor preferred in ACS), procedural anticoagulation with unfractionated heparin or bivalirudin, and intravenous cangrelor when a reliable oral effect cannot be guaranteed at the table."], "references": ["2021 ACC/AHA/SCAI Guideline for Coronary Artery Revascularization", "2023 ESC Guidelines for the Management of Acute Coronary Syndromes", "2024 ESC Guidelines for the Management of Chronic Coronary Syndromes", "2016 ACC/AHA Guideline Focused Update on Duration of Dual Antiplatelet Therapy in Coronary Artery Disease", "FAME and FAME 2 trials (fractional flow reserve-guided PCI)", "DEFINE-FLAIR and iFR-SWEDEHEART trials (instantaneous wave-free ratio)", "ULTIMATE, ILUMIEN III and ILUMIEN IV, RENOVATE-COMPLEX-PCI, and OCTOBER trials (intracoronary imaging-guided PCI)", "MATRIX and RIVAL trials (radial vs femoral access)", "VALIDATE-SWEDEHEART and BRIGHT-4 trials (bivalirudin)", "CHAMPION PHOENIX trial (cangrelor)", "TRITON-TIMI 38 (prasugrel) and PLATO (ticagrelor) trials", "Disrupt CAD III trial (intravascular lithotripsy for calcified lesions)", "COMPLETE and FLOWER-MI trials (non-culprit revascularization in STEMI)", "TOTAL and TASTE trials (routine aspiration thrombectomy in STEMI)"], "guidelines": [{"society": "ACC/AHA/SCAI", "text": "Radial arterial access is recommended over femoral access in patients with ACS undergoing PCI to reduce bleeding, vascular complications, and death.", "cor": "I", "loe": "A", "year": "2021"}, {"society": "ACC/AHA/SCAI", "text": "In selected intermediate coronary lesions, FFR or iFR is recommended to guide the decision to revascularize when ischemia has not been established by noninvasive testing.", "cor": "I", "loe": "A", "year": "2021"}, {"society": "ACC/AHA/SCAI", "text": "Intravascular ultrasound is reasonable to guide PCI, particularly for left main and complex lesions, to optimize stent sizing, expansion, and apposition.", "cor": "IIa", "loe": "B-R", "year": "2021"}, {"society": "ACC/AHA/SCAI", "text": "In patients with STEMI and multivessel disease who are hemodynamically stable, staged PCI of significant non-culprit lesions is reasonable to reduce cardiovascular events.", "cor": "IIa", "loe": "A", "year": "2021"}, {"society": "ESC", "text": "In ACS, prasugrel or ticagrelor is preferred over clopidogrel in addition to aspirin unless contraindicated (prasugrel contraindicated after prior stroke or TIA).", "cor": "I", "loe": "B", "year": "2023"}, {"society": "ACC/AHA", "text": "DAPT duration should be individualized by weighing ischemic against bleeding risk rather than applied as a fixed interval for all patients.", "cor": "I", "loe": "A", "year": "2016"}], "sections": [{"id": "learning-objectives", "title": "Learning objectives", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "This is a dedicated procedural module. It assumes you understand coronary anatomy, the acute coronary syndromes, and when a patient needs the cath lab. It builds the operator's reasoning layer: the tools on the table, the numbers that change the plan, and the complications you must recognize and treat within seconds."}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Choose vascular access and confirm collateral hand circulation before committing to the radial artery.", "Match a guide catheter to the target vessel and describe how backup support is generated.", "Select a guidewire by task, from the workhorse wire to the dedicated chronic total occlusion (CTO) wire.", "Sequence balloons and stents through predilation, deployment, and postdilation, and know when calcium modification must come first.", "Apply intracoronary imaging and coronary physiology to size, optimize, and defer.", "Recognize and manage perforation, no-reflow, dissection, side-branch occlusion, stent thrombosis, and access-site bleeding."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "text": "A first-year fellow is judged at the table on three reflexes: naming the tool for the task, reading the pressure and angiographic cues before they become an emergency, and treating the complication with the right drug or device without hesitation. Everything below is organized around those reflexes."}]}, {"id": "why-it-matters", "title": "Why it matters", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) is the highest-volume therapeutic procedure in cardiology. The equipment is deceptively simple to name and genuinely hard to use well. Access choice changes bleeding and mortality. Wire choice determines whether a lesion is crossed safely or a vessel is perforated. Imaging and physiology separate the lesions that need a stent from the lesions that do not, and separate a good stent result from an under-expanded stent that will thrombose."}, {"type": "p", "text": "The through-line of modern PCI is that the angiogram alone is insufficient. The lumenogram underestimates plaque burden, cannot measure ischemia, and cannot see stent under-expansion. Fellows who anchor on the two-dimensional silhouette make predictable errors. Fellows who add physiology and imaging make better decisions and fewer of them."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "The three questions that organize every case: Does this lesion cause ischemia (physiology)? What is the true vessel size and plaque composition (imaging)? Will it dilate, or does it need to be modified first (calcium assessment)? Answer those before the stent, not after."}]}, {"id": "access", "title": "Vascular access", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Access is the first decision and one of the most consequential. Radial-first access reduces access-site bleeding, vascular complications, and, in acute coronary syndrome (ACS), mortality (demonstrated in MATRIX and supported by RIVAL and meta-analyses). This is a guideline-supported quality standard, not an operator preference. Femoral access remains necessary for large-bore devices, some CTO and complex cases, and when both radials are unusable."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "Radial access", "def": "Puncture of the radial artery at the wrist. Lower bleeding, earlier ambulation, patient preference. Limited by artery size, spasm, tortuosity, and prior harvest. First choice for most diagnostic and PCI cases."}, {"term": "Femoral access", "def": "Puncture of the common femoral artery over the femoral head, below the inguinal ligament and above the bifurcation. Needed for large-bore access (structural, mechanical support, some CTO). Higher bleeding, including retroperitoneal hemorrhage."}, {"term": "Distal radial (anatomical snuffbox)", "def": "Alternative radial puncture in the snuffbox. May reduce radial artery occlusion and preserve the forearm radial for future access or as a bypass conduit."}]}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "Barbeau test", "def": "Preferred pre-radial assessment. A pulse oximeter is placed on the thumb while the radial artery is compressed. A persistent or recovering plethysmographic waveform (types A-C) confirms adequate ulnar and palmar arch collateral. Type D (no recovery of the waveform) is the abnormal result that argues against that radial."}, {"term": "Allen test", "def": "Older bedside test: compress radial and ulnar arteries, blanch the hand, release the ulnar, and time palmar reperfusion. Superseded by the more objective Barbeau test but still described. A prolonged (>2 second) or absent flush is abnormal."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "Mnemonic for Barbeau grades: A-B-C are Acceptable (waveform preserved or recovers), D is Denied (flat waveform, choose the other side). The Barbeau test replaced the Allen test because a pulse-oximetry waveform is objective and the old palmar-flush timing was not."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 2, "head": ["Radial spasm and access pearls"], "items": ["Give an intra-arterial vasodilator cocktail after sheath insertion (for example verapamil with nitroglycerin) to prevent spasm.", "Hydrophilic-coated sheaths reduce spasm and radial artery occlusion.", "Adequate procedural anticoagulation (typically weight-based unfractionated heparin) lowers radial artery occlusion.", "Patent hemostasis (compression that stops bleeding while preserving flow, confirmed by plethysmography) further lowers the rate of radial artery occlusion.", "For femoral access, ultrasound and fluoroscopic landmarking of the femoral head reduce high and low punctures; a high stick above the inguinal ligament is the setup for a retroperitoneal bleed."]}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Radial and femoral access anatomy and angiographic examples are best learned from labeled images.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia: vascular access imaging"}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "Hypotension after femoral access with a benign-appearing groin is retroperitoneal hemorrhage until proven otherwise. A puncture above the inferior epigastric artery or inguinal ligament bleeds into the retroperitoneum, where tamponade by the groin does not occur. Resuscitate, reverse anticoagulation, image with CT or ultrasound, and involve surgery or covered-stent and balloon tamponade early."}]}, {"id": "guide-catheters", "title": "Guide catheters and backup support", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The guide catheter is the rail for everything that follows. It must engage the coronary ostium coaxially, deliver contrast and pressure, and provide enough backup support to push equipment across the lesion. Guide selection is a trade-off between ease of engagement and support."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "Passive support", "def": "Backup generated by the guide shape bracing against the opposite aortic wall. Extra-backup shapes (EBU, XB, Voda) for the left system and Amplatz shapes provide more passive support than a Judkins curve."}, {"term": "Active support", "def": "Support generated by deep intubation or by advancing the guide during pushing. Higher support but higher risk of ostial or catheter-induced dissection."}, {"term": "Guide extension", "def": "A rapid-exchange mother-and-child extension catheter telescoped through the guide to deliver deep coaxial support and stent delivery in tortuous or calcified vessels."}]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "head": ["Target", "Common guide shapes", "Note"], "rows": [["Left coronary (LM/LAD/LCx)", "EBU/XB/Voda 3.5-4.0, Judkins Left", "Extra-backup shapes for complex or calcified left-sided PCI"], ["Right coronary", "Judkins Right, Amplatz Left, hockey-stick", "Amplatz or guide extension for a shepherd-crook or superiorly oriented RCA"], ["Saphenous vein graft", "Multipurpose, Amplatz Left, hockey-stick", "Consider distal embolic protection for degenerated grafts"], ["Radial-specific", "Ikari, Tiger/Jacky (diagnostic)", "Shapes designed to engage from the right radial with a single catheter"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "Guide catheter French size sets what you can deliver. A 6F guide handles most single-stent work and most imaging; two-stent bifurcation techniques, rotational atherectomy with larger burrs, and some IVUS or complex combinations may need 7F or 8F. Plan the access sheath around the biggest device you might need, not the first one."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "Pressure damping or ventricularization on engagement means the tip is obstructing flow, wedged, or against an ostial lesion. Do not power-inject. Disengage, reassess, and consider a side-hole guide or a smaller catheter. Injecting an obstructed left main can precipitate ischemia, ventricular fibrillation, or dissection."}]}, {"id": "guidewires", "title": "Coronary guidewires", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The guidewire is the single most important safety decision in PCI. Every device tracks over it, and the wrong wire in the wrong place perforates vessels or dissects them. Wires are built from a core (stainless steel or nitinol), a tip (shapeable), and a coating (hydrophilic or hydrophobic). They are classified by tip load (gram-force), coating, and support."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "Workhorse wire", "def": "The default wire for routine PCI. Soft, atraumatic, floppy tip with low tip load (roughly 1 gram), moderate support, hydrophobic or partially coated. Safe to steer through most native lesions and used to cross the great majority of lesions."}, {"term": "Polymer-jacketed / hydrophilic wire", "def": "A slippery full-polymer or hydrophilic coating that glides through tortuosity, thrombus, and tight or subtotal lesions. Trades tactile feedback for trackability. Because it is slippery and can enter the subintimal space silently, it carries a higher risk of dissection and distal perforation. Reserve for crossing difficult anatomy, then exchange for a workhorse wire before ballooning when possible."}, {"term": "Extra-support wire", "def": "A stiffer body that straightens tortuosity and delivers bulky or calcified equipment. The tip stays soft; the support comes from the shaft. Used to deliver stents in tortuous or calcified vessels and as a buddy wire."}]}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "CTO wire (tapered-tip / high gram-force)", "def": "Dedicated wires for chronic total occlusions. Escalation ranges from soft tapered polymer wires (for example a 0.009-inch tapered tip) that seek microchannels, to high-tip-load penetration wires (tip force well above 10 grams, for example a stiff tapered-tip wire) that puncture the proximal or distal cap. Tapered tips concentrate force on a small point to penetrate hard caps."}, {"term": "Antegrade CTO approach", "def": "Crossing from the proximal cap forward, with wire escalation, parallel-wire, or antegrade dissection re-entry (ADR) techniques when the wire tracks subintimally and must re-enter the true lumen distally."}, {"term": "Retrograde CTO approach", "def": "Crossing the occlusion backward through a collateral channel (septal or epicardial) into the distal vessel, used when the proximal cap is ambiguous or the antegrade route fails. Requires collateral crossing and often reverse controlled antegrade and retrograde tracking (reverse CART)."}]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "head": ["Wire type", "Tip load", "Coating", "Primary use"], "rows": [["Workhorse", "~1 g", "Hydrophobic/partial", "Routine crossing, default rail"], ["Polymer-jacketed / hydrophilic", "Low-moderate", "Full polymer / hydrophilic", "Tortuosity, thrombus, subtotal or difficult lesions"], ["Extra-support", "Low tip, stiff body", "Mixed", "Deliver stents in tortuous/calcified vessels; buddy wire"], ["CTO tapered soft", "Low, tapered", "Polymer", "Microchannel tracking through the occlusion"], ["CTO high gram-force", "High (>10 g), tapered", "Hydrophilic tip", "Puncturing hard proximal/distal caps"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "A polymer-jacketed wire that advances too far distally into a small vessel is a classic cause of guidewire-exit distal perforation, and the perforation may not be obvious until the sheath is out. Keep the tip in view, do not park slippery wires deep in small distal branches, and exchange to a workhorse wire once you have crossed."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 3, "text": "Mnemonic for wire escalation logic: Soft to Slippery to Stiff. Start with the soft workhorse; move to a slippery polymer wire for tortuosity or thrombus; escalate to stiff tapered high-gram-force wires only for hard caps and CTOs, and step back down as soon as you are through."}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Angiographic examples of CTO morphology (tapered vs blunt cap, collateral channels) are worth reviewing as labeled images.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia: coronary angiography"}]}, {"id": "balloons", "title": "Balloons: predilation and postdilation", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Balloons prepare the lesion, deploy or expand equipment, and finish the stent. The compliance of the balloon (how its diameter grows with pressure) determines whether you are gently opening a lesion or focally cracking calcium at high pressure. Getting predilation right is often the difference between a fully expanded stent and an under-expanded one."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "Semi-compliant balloon", "def": "Grows modestly with increasing pressure. Used for predilation and general work. Forgiving but can grow beyond nominal at high pressure and injure the reference segment."}, {"term": "Non-compliant (NC) balloon", "def": "Holds its diameter across a wide pressure range and tolerates high pressures. Used for postdilation and for high-pressure expansion of resistant or calcified lesions and stents. The workhorse for stent optimization."}, {"term": "Cutting balloon", "def": "A balloon with mounted microsurgical blades (atherotomes) that score the plaque as it inflates, controlling dilation and reducing balloon slippage (the watermelon-seed effect). Useful for fibrocalcific and in-stent restenosis lesions."}, {"term": "Scoring balloon", "def": "A balloon with an external nitinol scoring element or wire that creates controlled fracture lines in plaque at lower pressure, reducing slippage and improving expansion of resistant lesions."}, {"term": "Drug-coated balloon (DCB)", "def": "A balloon coated with an antiproliferative agent (usually paclitaxel or a limus) that transfers drug to the wall without leaving metal. Established for in-stent restenosis and used selectively in small-vessel and high-bleeding-risk lesions."}]}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "head": ["Balloon lesion preparation"], "items": ["Predilate resistant, calcified, or tight lesions to confirm the lesion will expand and to allow the stent to cross and expand fully.", "If a semi-compliant balloon will not fully expand, escalate to a non-compliant balloon at high pressure, then to a scoring or cutting balloon.", "If the lesion still will not yield, stop and modify calcium (atherectomy or lithotripsy) before placing a stent.", "Deploy the stent at nominal-to-moderate pressure.", "Postdilate with a non-compliant balloon sized to the reference lumen, at high pressure, to optimize expansion and apposition, especially in calcified, long, bifurcation, or left main lesions, and confirm by imaging."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "The single most important balloon lesson: an undilatable lesion is a contraindication to stenting until it is modified. If a non-compliant balloon will not expand the lesion, do not force a stent into a segment it cannot fully expand. Under-expansion is the dominant mechanical cause of stent thrombosis and restenosis."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "Postdilation is not optional in calcified vessels, long stents, bifurcations, or the left main. Use a non-compliant balloon sized to the media-to-media reference, and confirm expansion by IVUS or OCT rather than by the angiographic silhouette, which routinely overestimates expansion."}]}, {"id": "stents", "title": "Stents and drug-eluting technology", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The stent scaffolds the vessel and prevents acute recoil. Modern PCI uses drug-eluting stents (DES) almost exclusively. A DES is a thin metallic scaffold coated with an antiproliferative drug on a polymer that controls elution, suppressing the neointimal hyperplasia that drove restenosis in the bare-metal era."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "head": ["Generation", "Examples", "Advance"], "rows": [["Bare-metal stent", "Historical", "Solved acute recoil; high restenosis remained"], ["First-generation DES", "Sirolimus-, paclitaxel-eluting", "Cut restenosis; durable polymers raised late stent thrombosis"], ["Second-generation DES", "Everolimus-, zotarolimus-eluting", "Thin cobalt-chromium or platinum-chromium struts, biocompatible polymers; current standard"], ["Newer platforms", "Biodegradable-polymer and ultrathin-strut DES", "Aim to reduce very-late events and shorten required DAPT"]]}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "Antiproliferative drug", "def": "The -limus family (sirolimus, everolimus, zotarolimus, biolimus) inhibits mTOR and smooth-muscle proliferation. Paclitaxel (first-generation) stabilizes microtubules. Current DES are predominantly limus-eluting."}, {"term": "Strut thickness", "def": "Thinner struts (now well below 100 microns) heal faster, reduce restenosis and stent thrombosis, and deliver more easily. A major driver of second-generation and ultrathin performance."}, {"term": "In-stent restenosis (ISR)", "def": "Renarrowing within a stent from neointimal hyperplasia or neoatherosclerosis. Evaluate the mechanism with imaging: under-expansion is mechanical and treated with high-pressure NC balloons; biological ISR is treated with a drug-coated balloon or repeat DES."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "A stent result has three imaging pillars: expansion (adequate minimal stent area for the vessel), apposition (struts against the wall), and no edge problem (no significant edge dissection or residual disease at the landing zone). Angiography reliably shows none of these; imaging shows all three."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Bioresorbable vascular scaffolds were designed to disappear after healing but showed higher scaffold thrombosis and were withdrawn from routine use. The lesson stands: strut thickness, complete expansion, and full apposition matter more than the theoretical appeal of a disappearing scaffold."}]}, {"id": "imaging", "title": "Intracoronary imaging: IVUS vs OCT", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Intravascular ultrasound (IVUS) and optical coherence tomography (OCT) turn the lumenogram into a cross-sectional map of the vessel wall. They answer questions angiography cannot: true vessel size, plaque burden and calcium, the mechanism of restenosis, and whether a stent is fully expanded and apposed. Imaging-guided PCI improves outcomes in complex and left main disease (ULTIMATE, ILUMIEN IV, RENOVATE-COMPLEX-PCI, OCTOBER)."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "head": ["Feature", "IVUS", "OCT"], "rows": [["Energy source", "Sound (ultrasound)", "Near-infrared light"], ["Resolution", "Lower (~100-150 microns)", "Higher (~10-20 microns)"], ["Penetration", "Deeper; sees the full vessel and external elastic lamina", "Shallower; superb surface and strut detail"], ["Blood clearing", "Not required", "Requires contrast or saline flush to clear blood"], ["Best for", "Left main, large vessels, ostial/aorto-ostial, contrast-sparing", "Edge dissection, strut apposition, thrombus, calcium arc/thickness, restenosis mechanism"]]}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "Minimal stent area (MSA)", "def": "The smallest cross-sectional lumen area inside the stent, the strongest imaging predictor of stent patency. General non-left-main targets are roughly greater than 5.5 mm2 by IVUS and about 4.5-5.0 mm2 by OCT, or a relative expansion above 80-90% of the reference. Left main and ostial LAD targets are larger."}, {"term": "Reference vessel and landing zone", "def": "Imaging sizes the stent to the media-to-media (IVUS) or lumen (OCT) reference and picks landing zones in relatively disease-free segments to avoid stenting into plaque and creating edge dissection or geographic miss."}, {"term": "Calcium arc and thickness", "def": "OCT quantifies calcium arc, thickness, and length; a large arc (roughly >180 degrees), thick, long calcium predicts under-expansion and flags the need for atherectomy or lithotripsy before stenting."}]}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 2, "head": ["Imaging-guided optimization sequence"], "items": ["Pre-stent: size the vessel (reference diameter and length), assess plaque and calcium, and choose landing zones.", "Choose the stent diameter and length from the reference, not the angiogram.", "Post-stent: measure the minimal stent area and compare to the reference for expansion.", "Check apposition (struts against the wall) and stent edges (dissection, residual plaque).", "Correct under-expansion with a high-pressure NC balloon, and malapposition or edge dissection as indicated, then re-image."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "Mnemonic for reading any stent on imaging: A-P-E. Apposition (struts on the wall), Position/expansion (adequate MSA vs reference), Edges (no flow-limiting dissection or residual disease). If all three are clean, the stent is optimized."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "For left main and complex bifurcation PCI, imaging is close to standard of care. Trials of imaging-guided PCI in complex lesions showed fewer target-vessel and stent-related events than angiography-guided PCI. When contrast load is the constraint (chronic kidney disease), IVUS is favored because it does not require a contrast flush."}]}, {"id": "physiology", "title": "Coronary physiology: FFR and iFR", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Physiology answers the question the eye cannot: does this intermediate lesion actually cause ischemia? Pressure-wire indices convert an ambiguous 40-70% stenosis into a decision. FFR-guided and resting-index-guided PCI reduce unnecessary stenting and improve outcomes compared with treating every angiographic narrowing."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "Fractional flow reserve (FFR)", "def": "The ratio of distal coronary pressure to aortic pressure at maximal hyperemia (induced by intravenous or intracoronary adenosine). It estimates the fraction of normal maximal flow the diseased vessel still allows. Ischemic threshold is 0.80 or below; defer above 0.80. Validated by FAME and FAME 2."}, {"term": "Instantaneous wave-free ratio (iFR)", "def": "A resting index measured during the diastolic wave-free period, when microvascular resistance is naturally low, so no adenosine is needed. Ischemic threshold is 0.89 or below; defer above 0.89. Non-inferior to FFR for outcomes in DEFINE-FLAIR and iFR-SWEDEHEART."}, {"term": "Other resting indices (RFR, DFR, Pd/Pa)", "def": "Resting full-cycle ratio and diastolic ratios track iFR with a similar 0.89 cutoff. Resting Pd/Pa is a screening ratio, not a definitive threshold."}]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "head": ["Index", "Basis", "Ischemic cutoff", "Defer above"], "rows": [["FFR", "Maximal hyperemia (adenosine)", "<=0.80", ">0.80"], ["iFR", "Resting wave-free diastole", "<=0.89", ">0.89"], ["RFR / DFR", "Resting whole-cycle or diastolic ratio", "<=0.89", ">0.89"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "The FFR 0.75-0.80 gray zone is a judgment zone, not a bright line. FAME used 0.80 to favor sensitivity for ischemia. Interpret values here with symptoms, vessel territory, and any noninvasive ischemia data before committing to a stent."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "Do not trust FFR in the culprit vessel acutely after STEMI. Microvascular stunning raises resistance and blunts hyperemia, falsely raising the FFR of the infarct artery. Treat the culprit on angiographic and clinical grounds. For stable non-culprit lesions, staged complete revascularization is reasonable (COMPLETE), though FFR guidance of non-culprit lesions was not superior to angiographic guidance in FLOWER-MI."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "FFR assumes the microcirculation can be maximally and uniformly dilated. In severe left ventricular hypertrophy, prior infarction, or microvascular disease, hyperemia is impaired and FFR can misrepresent epicardial significance. This is where coronary flow reserve and the index of microcirculatory resistance add information the epicardial number cannot."}]}, {"id": "calcium", "title": "Calcium modification: atherectomy and lithotripsy", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Calcium is the enemy of full stent expansion. Heavily calcified lesions resist balloons, prevent stents from expanding, and predict under-expansion, restenosis, and stent thrombosis. Recognizing the undilatable calcified lesion early, and modifying it before the stent, is a defining skill of competent PCI."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "Rotational atherectomy (rotablation)", "def": "A diamond-coated burr rotating at high speed (roughly 140,000-180,000 rpm) sands away inelastic superficial calcium by differential cutting, leaving elastic tissue intact. For undilatable or uncrossable heavily calcified lesions. Risks slow-flow or no-reflow, perforation, and burr entrapment."}, {"term": "Orbital atherectomy", "def": "An eccentrically mounted diamond crown that sands calcium as it orbits, with an increasing sanding diameter at higher speeds and the ability to treat both faces of the vessel with one crown."}, {"term": "Intravascular lithotripsy (IVL)", "def": "A balloon-mounted catheter delivers acoustic pressure pulses that fracture both superficial and deep calcium while sparing soft tissue, at low balloon pressure. Modifies calcium the balloon alone cannot crack and is technically straightforward compared with atherectomy (Disrupt CAD III)."}]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "head": ["Tool", "Mechanism", "Best niche", "Signature risk"], "rows": [["NC / scoring / cutting balloon", "High-pressure or focal fracture", "Mild-moderate calcium, ISR", "Slippage, edge dissection"], ["Rotational atherectomy", "Differential sanding of superficial calcium", "Undilatable, uncrossable, balloon-refractory", "Slow-flow, perforation, burr entrapment"], ["Orbital atherectomy", "Orbiting crown sands both faces", "Concentric/eccentric superficial calcium", "Slow-flow, perforation"], ["Intravascular lithotripsy", "Sonic pressure waves fracture calcium", "Deep calcium, large concentric rings, expansion failure", "Rare capture-beat ectopy; balloon rupture"]]}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 2, "head": ["Approach to the calcified lesion"], "items": ["Suspect calcium from the angiogram and, better, quantify arc and thickness by OCT or IVUS.", "Try a non-compliant balloon; if it will not expand, do not stent.", "For superficial, undilatable, or uncrossable calcium, choose rotational or orbital atherectomy.", "For deep or concentric calcium and expansion failure, choose intravascular lithotripsy (or combine with atherectomy).", "Confirm modification by re-imaging (calcium fractures on OCT), then stent and postdilate to target MSA."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "Mnemonic for when to modify: the R-O-C-K lesions. Refractory to NC balloon, Obviously calcified on imaging, Cannot cross with equipment, and Kissing under-expansion after a stent. Any of these means modify the calcium rather than push harder."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 3, "text": "Rotational atherectomy in a vessel with impaired flow, severe left ventricular dysfunction, or a large territory can precipitate profound bradycardia and slow-flow. Use short ablation runs, a flush cocktail through the guide, temporary pacing readiness for the right or dominant vessel, and stop at the first sign of slow-flow."}]}, {"id": "complications", "title": "Complications and their management", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The fellow's value at the table is greatest when something goes wrong. Each of these has a recognition cue and a first move that must be automatic. Hesitation, not the complication itself, is what turns a manageable event into a catastrophe."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "Coronary perforation", "def": "Contrast extravasation from the vessel. Graded by the Ellis classification. Risk factors include atherectomy, oversized balloons or stents, stiff and polymer wires distally, and CTO work."}, {"term": "No-reflow", "def": "Reduced antegrade flow (TIMI 0-2) despite a patent epicardial vessel, from distal embolization, microvascular spasm, and microvascular obstruction. Common after atherectomy, thrombotic lesions, and vein-graft PCI."}, {"term": "Coronary dissection / abrupt closure", "def": "A luminal flap or contrast staining that reduces or stops flow. Iatrogenic dissection can propagate. The reflex is to stent the entry point promptly and avoid extending it."}]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "head": ["Ellis grade", "Angiographic finding", "Typical management"], "rows": [["I", "Extraluminal crater or staining without extravasation", "Often conservative; prolonged balloon; observe"], ["II", "Pericardial or myocardial blush without a jet", "Prolonged low-pressure balloon, reverse anticoagulation, observe for tamponade"], ["III", "Frank extravasation through a >=1 mm hole (brisk jet)", "Emergency: prolonged balloon occlusion, covered stent, reverse anticoagulation, pericardiocentesis if tamponade"], ["III cavity spilling", "Perforation into a cardiac chamber, coronary sinus, or vein", "May tolerate better hemodynamically; still requires a closure or embolization decision"]]}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "head": ["Perforation management sequence"], "items": ["Inflate a balloon across or proximal to the perforation immediately to tamponade the leak.", "Reverse anticoagulation (protamine for heparin), but weigh the risk of stent thrombosis if a fresh stent is in place.", "Assess hemodynamics and echo for tamponade; perform pericardiocentesis if tamponade develops.", "For a persistent grade III leak, deploy a covered (PTFE-covered) stent across the perforation.", "For a distal wire-exit perforation, consider coil, fat, or microsphere embolization of the distal branch.", "Escalate to surgery for uncontrolled bleeding."]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "head": ["Complication", "Recognition", "First moves"], "rows": [["No-reflow", "Patent vessel, TIMI 0-2, chest pain, ST changes, hypotension", "Intracoronary vasodilators (adenosine, verapamil, nicardipine, nitroprusside); support blood pressure; avoid more manipulation"], ["Dissection / abrupt closure", "Flap, staining, abrupt flow loss", "Keep wire position, stent the entry, do not balloon distal to it"], ["Side-branch occlusion", "Loss of a jailed branch after main-vessel stenting", "Rewire the branch through the stent, kissing-balloon or provisional side-branch stent per Medina and branch size"], ["Stent thrombosis", "Acute STEMI in a stented territory", "Emergency angiography, aspiration or balloon, correct the mechanism (under-expansion), potent antiplatelet with GPI or cangrelor"], ["Air embolism", "Sudden ischemia after injection, filling defect", "100% oxygen, aspiration, forceful saline flush, support hemodynamics"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "No-reflow is treated pharmacologically, not mechanically. The instinct to balloon or pass more equipment makes it worse. The move is an intracoronary vasodilator delivered distally through a microcatheter or over-the-wire balloon (adenosine, verapamil, nicardipine, or nitroprusside), while you support the blood pressure. Nitroglycerin treats epicardial spasm and does not reverse microvascular no-reflow."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "Stent thrombosis timing (ARC)", "def": "Acute (<24 hours), subacute (24 hours to 30 days), late (30 days to 1 year), very late (>1 year). Definite (angiographic or pathologic confirmation), probable, or possible by Academic Research Consortium criteria."}, {"term": "Mechanical vs biological triggers", "def": "Early stent thrombosis is usually mechanical (under-expansion, malapposition, edge dissection, uncovered thrombus) plus antiplatelet interruption. Very-late events skew toward neoatherosclerosis and uncovered struts. Image every stent thrombosis to find the cause."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "Premature discontinuation of dual antiplatelet therapy is the leading modifiable cause of early stent thrombosis, which carries high mortality. Before any surgery in a recently stented patient, the interruption decision is a documented, multidisciplinary one, not a reflexive stop."}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Angiographic appearances of perforation with pericardial blush, no-reflow, and dissection flaps are best reviewed as labeled cases.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia: coronary complications imaging"}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "Access-site: radial artery occlusion", "def": "Thrombotic occlusion of the radial after sheath removal. Reduced by adequate procedural anticoagulation and patent hemostasis. Often asymptomatic when the palmar arch is intact; treat with anticoagulation or ipsilateral ulnar compression to restore flow."}, {"term": "Access-site: femoral hematoma / pseudoaneurysm", "def": "Hematoma from a groin bleed; a pseudoaneurysm is a contained rupture with a neck communicating with the artery. Diagnose the pseudoaneurysm by ultrasound (to-and-fro flow); treat with ultrasound-guided compression or thrombin injection, and surgery if large or expanding."}, {"term": "Access-site: retroperitoneal hemorrhage", "def": "Occult bleed from a high femoral puncture. Hypotension, flank or back pain, falling hematocrit with a benign groin. Resuscitate, reverse anticoagulation, CT or ultrasound, and balloon tamponade, covered stent, or surgery."}, {"term": "Access-site: AV fistula", "def": "Communication between the punctured artery and adjacent vein (low through-and-through puncture). Bruit and thrill; small ones close spontaneously, larger ones need compression or repair."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "Mnemonic for the table emergencies: the 4 D's plus flow. Dissection (stent the entry), Deflation-refractory perforation (balloon, cover, drain), Dead flow / no-reflow (intracoronary vasodilator), and Device thrombosis (open and fix the mechanism). Access bleeding is the fifth, and it kills quietly."}]}, {"id": "special-scenarios", "title": "Special lesions: bifurcation, left main, and STEMI", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Beyond the focal native lesion, three scenarios recur on call and reward a rehearsed default. Bifurcations and the left main punish improvisation; the STEMI culprit rewards restraint about adjunctive maneuvers."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "Bifurcation: provisional stenting", "def": "The default strategy for most bifurcations. Stent the main vessel, keep a wire in the side branch, and treat the side branch only if it is compromised. Favored over routine two-stent approaches unless the side branch is large and diseased."}, {"term": "Proximal optimization technique (POT)", "def": "Post-deployment inflation of a short non-compliant balloon in the proximal main vessel, sized to the proximal reference, to appose struts, correct the step-up in diameter, and open the cell facing the side branch. A core step after main-vessel stenting."}, {"term": "Two-stent techniques", "def": "DK-crush, culotte, T and TAP, and mini-crush are reserved for large, significantly diseased side branches. DK-crush outperformed provisional for true distal left main bifurcation lesions in DKCRUSH-V."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "The Medina classification (1,1,1 style notation for proximal main, distal main, and side branch) standardizes how a bifurcation is described and communicated. Pair it with intracoronary imaging for the left main, where under-sizing and incomplete expansion at the ostium drive events."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "text": "In primary PCI for STEMI, routine aspiration thrombectomy is not recommended: TOTAL and TASTE showed no mortality benefit and TOTAL signaled increased stroke. Reserve aspiration for selective bailout with large residual thrombus. Direct stenting of the culprit is reasonable when the lesion and thrombus burden allow."}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Angiographic bifurcation anatomy and left main morphology are worth reviewing as labeled images.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia: coronary angiography"}]}, {"id": "antithrombotics", "title": "Periprocedural antiplatelet and anticoagulation", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "PCI creates a thrombogenic surface. The antithrombotic plan has two arms: platelet inhibition (aspirin plus a P2Y12 inhibitor, with intravenous options at the table) and procedural anticoagulation (heparin or bivalirudin, with selective glycoprotein IIb/IIIa inhibitors). Every choice trades ischemic protection against bleeding, and bleeding is prognostically as important as ischemia."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "head": ["Drug", "Mechanism", "Load", "Maintenance", "Key contraindication", "Monitoring / notes"], "rows": [["Aspirin", "Irreversible COX-1 / thromboxane inhibition", "162-325 mg chewed", "75-100 mg daily", "Active bleeding, true aspirin allergy", "Backbone of DAPT; low-dose long term"], ["Clopidogrel", "Prodrug, irreversible P2Y12", "300-600 mg", "75 mg daily", "Active bleeding", "CYP2C19 loss-of-function reduces efficacy; weakest of the three"], ["Prasugrel", "Prodrug, irreversible P2Y12 (potent)", "60 mg", "10 mg daily (5 mg if <60 kg or age >=75)", "Prior stroke/TIA (harm); active bleeding", "No routine monitoring; preferred in ACS PCI where not contraindicated"], ["Ticagrelor", "Reversible, direct-acting P2Y12 (potent)", "180 mg", "90 mg twice daily", "Prior intracranial hemorrhage, severe hepatic disease", "Dyspnea, ventricular pauses; avoid strong CYP3A inhibitors/inducers; keep aspirin low-dose"], ["Cangrelor", "IV reversible, direct-acting P2Y12", "30 mcg/kg IV bolus", "4 mcg/kg/min IV infusion", "Active bleeding", "Ultra-fast on/off (offset within ~1 hour); bridge to oral P2Y12; do not start oral clopidogrel or prasugrel during infusion"]]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "head": ["Anticoagulant", "Mechanism", "Dose", "Target / monitoring", "Note"], "rows": [["Unfractionated heparin", "Antithrombin-mediated Xa/IIa inhibition", "70-100 U/kg (no GPI); 50-70 U/kg with GPI", "ACT 250-300 s (with GPI ~200-250 s)", "Reversible with protamine; default procedural anticoagulant"], ["Bivalirudin", "Direct thrombin inhibitor", "0.75 mg/kg bolus, 1.75 mg/kg/h infusion", "Predictable effect; less bleeding vs heparin plus GPI", "MATRIX, VALIDATE-SWEDEHEART, BRIGHT-4; a full-dose post-PCI infusion helps cover early stent thrombosis risk in STEMI"], ["GP IIb/IIIa inhibitor (eptifibatide, tirofiban, abciximab)", "Block the final common platelet aggregation pathway", "Weight-based bolus plus infusion", "Watch platelets (thrombocytopenia)", "Bailout for large thrombus burden or no-reflow; increases bleeding, so use selectively"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "Mnemonic for P2Y12 potency and pitfalls: Clopidogrel is Cautious (weak, CYP2C19-dependent), Prasugrel Punches (potent, but Prior stroke is Prohibited), Ticagrelor is Twice-daily and Talks back (dyspnea, reversible), Cangrelor is the Cannula drug (IV, on and off within an hour)."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "text": "Cangrelor fills the gap when a reliable oral P2Y12 effect cannot be guaranteed at the table: the patient who cannot swallow, is intubated, is vomiting, or is in cardiogenic shock with unpredictable gut absorption, or has not been pre-loaded. It works within minutes and offsets within about an hour of stopping. Because it competes at the receptor, start clopidogrel or prasugrel only after the infusion ends; ticagrelor can be given during the infusion. CHAMPION PHOENIX showed reduced periprocedural ischemic events."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "Ticagrelor plus high-dose aspirin blunted ticagrelor's benefit in the PLATO US cohort; keep aspirin at 75-100 mg. Prasugrel after a prior stroke or TIA caused net harm in TRITON-TIMI 38 and is contraindicated. These two errors are common and testable."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 3, "head": ["Duration and de-escalation logic"], "items": ["Standard DAPT after DES is aspirin plus a P2Y12 inhibitor, with duration individualized by ischemic versus bleeding risk rather than a single fixed interval.", "High bleeding risk favors shorter DAPT, then P2Y12 monotherapy (an increasingly common strategy after an early period).", "High ischemic risk with acceptable bleeding risk favors longer or more potent therapy.", "In ACS, a potent P2Y12 inhibitor (prasugrel or ticagrelor) is preferred over clopidogrel unless contraindicated.", "On triple therapy with an oral anticoagulant, minimize the aspirin exposure period and favor a P2Y12 inhibitor plus anticoagulant to reduce bleeding."]}]}, {"id": "putting-it-together", "title": "Putting it together at the table", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "A clean case is a sequence of correct small decisions. The operator who names the tool for each task, checks physiology before stenting the ambiguous lesion, images the complex or left main result, modifies calcium before forcing a stent, and reacts to complications with the right drug or device produces reproducibly good outcomes."}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "head": ["A general PCI workflow"], "items": ["Choose access: radial-first, confirm the arch with Barbeau; ultrasound-guided femoral when large-bore is needed.", "Engage with a guide sized for the largest device you might use, watching the pressure waveform.", "Cross with a workhorse wire; escalate to slippery or stiff wires only as the anatomy demands, and step back down.", "Interrogate the intermediate lesion with FFR or a resting index; defer if not ischemic.", "Prepare the lesion: predilate, and modify calcium before stenting if it will not expand.", "Size the stent from imaging or the reference, deploy, and postdilate with a non-compliant balloon.", "Confirm the result by imaging: apposition, expansion (minimal stent area), and clean edges.", "Match the antithrombotic plan to ischemic and bleeding risk, and hold the reflexes for perforation, no-reflow, dissection, and thrombosis ready."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "text": "The recurring fellowship lesson: the angiogram is a starting point, not a verdict. Physiology tells you whether to treat, imaging tells you how well you treated, calcium assessment tells you whether you can treat, and antithrombotic strategy tells you whether the result will last. Operators who use all four make fewer stents and better ones."}]}], "quiz": [{"stem": "A 68-year-old man undergoes PCI of a heavily calcified proximal LAD. After deploying a drug-eluting stent, the operator notes the stent looks under-expanded on angiography. IVUS confirms a minimal stent area of 3.8 mm2 with a 300-degree superficial calcium arc and incomplete expansion despite a non-compliant balloon at 20 atm. What is the most appropriate next step?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Accept the result and finish the case"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Deploy a second stent inside the first"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Perform calcium modification with rotational atherectomy or intravascular lithotripsy, then re-expand"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Administer intracoronary nitroglycerin and re-image"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Reverse anticoagulation and remove all equipment"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "An under-expanded stent in a heavily calcified vessel with a large calcium arc that resisted high-pressure non-compliant ballooning is the classic setup for stent thrombosis and restenosis. The calcium must be modified. Intravascular lithotripsy can fracture calcium even through a deployed stent, and rotational atherectomy addresses superficial calcium; either allows subsequent full expansion. Adding a second stent inside an under-expanded one does not solve the mechanical problem. Nitroglycerin treats spasm, not calcium. The ideal sequence modifies calcium before stenting, but the recovery move remains modification then re-expansion."}, {"stem": "During primary PCI for an inferior STEMI, after stenting the RCA the operator sees a widely patent epicardial vessel but TIMI 1 antegrade flow, with recurrent chest pain and hypotension. There is no dissection or distal cutoff. What is the best immediate management?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Deploy an additional stent distally"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Inflate a balloon across the mid-vessel"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Administer intracoronary adenosine, verapamil, or nicardipine and support blood pressure"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Give intracoronary nitroglycerin as the definitive treatment"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Reverse anticoagulation with protamine"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "This is no-reflow: a patent epicardial artery with impaired flow from microvascular obstruction and distal embolization. The treatment is pharmacologic and directed at the microcirculation with intracoronary vasodilators (adenosine, verapamil, nicardipine, or nitroprusside), delivered distally when possible, while supporting the blood pressure. Additional mechanical manipulation worsens it. Nitroglycerin relieves epicardial spasm but does not reverse microvascular no-reflow. Reversing anticoagulation risks stent thrombosis and does not address the problem."}, {"stem": "A 55-year-old woman with stable angina has a 60% mid-LAD stenosis on angiography and no prior ischemia testing. FFR across the lesion is 0.86 and iFR is 0.93. What is the most appropriate management?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Deploy a drug-eluting stent"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Defer PCI and continue optimal medical therapy"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Refer for coronary artery bypass grafting"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Perform intravascular ultrasound and stent if the minimal lumen area is small"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Repeat FFR after intracoronary nitroglycerin"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Both indices are above their ischemic thresholds (FFR above 0.80, iFR above 0.89), so the lesion is not flow-limiting. FAME 2 and the resting-index trials (DEFINE-FLAIR, iFR-SWEDEHEART) support deferring PCI for non-ischemic intermediate lesions and continuing medical therapy. Stenting a physiologically insignificant lesion adds procedural risk without benefit. Imaging measures anatomy, not ischemia, and does not override a reassuring physiology result here."}, {"stem": "During PCI of a tortuous RCA with a polymer-jacketed guidewire, the operator injects contrast and sees a brisk jet of extravasation into the pericardial space through an evident hole. The patient's blood pressure begins to fall. Which set of actions is most appropriate as the immediate response?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Continue the case; grade I perforations seal spontaneously"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Inflate a balloon across the perforation, assess for tamponade with echo and perform pericardiocentesis if needed, and prepare a covered stent"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Give intravenous heparin to prevent thrombus at the perforation site"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Immediately remove the guidewire and all equipment"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Administer intracoronary vasodilators"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "A brisk contrast jet through a hole with hemodynamic decline is an Ellis grade III perforation, a table emergency. The immediate move is prolonged balloon inflation across the perforation to tamponade the leak, echocardiographic assessment for tamponade with pericardiocentesis if it develops, reversal of anticoagulation weighed against stent thrombosis risk, and a covered (PTFE) stent for a persistent grade III leak. Adding heparin worsens bleeding. Removing the wire loses access needed to deploy a covered stent. Vasodilators treat no-reflow, not perforation."}, {"stem": "A patient in cardiogenic shock from an anterior STEMI is intubated and vomiting, and the team is uncertain whether oral antiplatelet loading will be absorbed before emergent PCI. Which agent best provides reliable, rapid, and rapidly reversible P2Y12 inhibition at the table?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Clopidogrel 600 mg via nasogastric tube"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Prasugrel 60 mg via nasogastric tube"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Intravenous cangrelor bolus and infusion"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Subcutaneous enoxaparin"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Warfarin loading"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "Oral P2Y12 inhibitors depend on gut absorption and hepatic activation, both unreliable in shock with impaired perfusion and vomiting. Cangrelor is an intravenous, direct-acting, reversible P2Y12 inhibitor with onset within minutes and offset within about an hour, ideal when a dependable oral effect cannot be guaranteed; CHAMPION PHOENIX showed reduced periprocedural ischemic events. Because it competes at the receptor, oral clopidogrel or prasugrel should be started only after the infusion ends. Enoxaparin and warfarin are anticoagulants, not P2Y12 inhibitors."}, {"stem": "Before radial access, a pulse oximeter placed on the thumb shows loss of the plethysmographic waveform when the radial artery is compressed, with no recovery over two minutes (Barbeau type D). What is the most appropriate action?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Proceed with right radial access as planned"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Use the contralateral radial or a femoral approach"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Proceed but use a smaller sheath"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Give intra-arterial verapamil and proceed regardless"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Perform the procedure without any anticoagulation to protect the artery"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "A Barbeau type D result means the plethysmographic waveform does not recover with radial compression, indicating inadequate ulnar and palmar arch collateral to that hand. Using that radial risks hand ischemia if the radial occludes. The appropriate step is to choose the contralateral radial or a femoral approach. Sheath size and vasodilators do not correct absent collateral flow, and omitting anticoagulation increases radial occlusion risk rather than protecting the hand."}]};
